# DOO slice 1 local-dev environment.
# Copy to `.env` and `export $(grep -v '^#' .env | xargs)` (or use direnv).
# These are the variable names the CLI actually reads (all `DOO_`-prefixed).
# The values below match the credentials in `docker-compose.yml` — the CLI's
# built-in defaults do NOT (they assume neo4j/password + minioadmin), so you
# must export these to talk to the compose stack. Never commit a populated `.env`.

# ----- Neo4j (L3 graph) -----
DOO_NEO4J_URI=bolt://localhost:7687
DOO_NEO4J_USER=neo4j
DOO_NEO4J_PASSWORD=doo-dev-password

# ----- Redis (L1 streams + kill-switch lease) -----
DOO_REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379/0

# ----- MinIO / S3 (request/response bodies) -----
DOO_S3_ENDPOINT=http://localhost:9000
DOO_S3_ACCESS_KEY=doo-dev
DOO_S3_SECRET_KEY=doo-dev-password
DOO_S3_BUCKET=doo-blobs

# ----- Planner LLM (slice 3 — `doo planner propose` C2 hypothesis generation) -----
# The planner calls a model through litellm. Pick the model with DOO_PLANNER_MODEL;
# choose ONE of the two auth modes below. Only needed when running an LLM generator
# (e.g. `-g c2`); deterministic C1 needs none of this. Never commit a real key.
#
# DOO_PLANNER_MODEL — which model (litellm id). Default: claude-opus-4-8.
#   Anthropic-direct ids are provider-prefixed, e.g.:
#     anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6   (Sonnet 4.6)
#     anthropic/claude-opus-4-8     (Opus 4.8)
#   Gateway / OpenAI-compatible ids use the openai/ prefix, e.g. openai/gpt-4o.
# DOO_PLANNER_MODEL=anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6
#
# Mode A — Anthropic API directly (just a key; model must be an anthropic/... id):
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
#
# Mode B — a model provider URL + key (LiteLLM gateway / local proxy / any
#   OpenAI-compatible endpoint; model is typically an openai/<name> id):
# DOO_PLANNER_API_BASE=https://your-gateway.example.com/v1
# DOO_PLANNER_API_KEY=your-gateway-key
#
# DOO_PLANNER_TIMEOUT_S — bound on a single proposing attempt (seconds). Default 60.
#   Generators call the model once per gap, sequentially; a stalled gateway would
#   otherwise hang the whole `propose` run. A timed-out call is recorded as an
#   `LLMSkipped(code="call_timeout")` and the run continues. Set to 0 (or empty)
#   to disable the bound.
# DOO_PLANNER_TIMEOUT_S=60
#
# DOO_PLANNER_TOOL_CHOICE — `force` (default) or `auto`. `force` pins the
#   `propose_test` tool so the response is guaranteed-structured. Some models
#   (e.g. anthropic/claude-fable-5) reject forced tool use with a 400; set
#   `auto` for those — the system prompt still instructs a single tool call, and a
#   missing one is recorded as `LLMSkipped(code="proposal_error")`.
# DOO_PLANNER_TOOL_CHOICE=force
#
# DOO_PLANNER_TEMPERATURE — sampling temperature. Default 0.0 (most-reproducible
#   proposals). Set to `none` (or leave the value empty) to OMIT the parameter
#   entirely — required for models that reject it (e.g. anthropic/claude-fable-5,
#    which 400 with "`temperature` is deprecated").
# DOO_PLANNER_TEMPERATURE=0.0
#
# DOO_PLANNER_NUM_RETRIES — litellm per-call retry count. Default 0.
#   Re-running `propose` is the retry (idempotent commits per ADR-0007), so the
#   per-call default is zero and the run is capped at roughly
#   `gaps × DOO_PLANNER_TIMEOUT_S × (DOO_PLANNER_NUM_RETRIES + 1)`. Raise this for
#   a flaky gateway only if re-running the whole command is impractical.
# DOO_PLANNER_NUM_RETRIES=0

# ----- OPA (slice 4 — the dispatcher's authoritative policy gate, ADR-0046) -----
# `doo dispatch run` evaluates the generated-from-Scope bundle via the `opa`
# binary. Either install the static binary on PATH (recommended — also runs
# `opa test src/doo/policy/` and the dual-path tests):
#   curl -L -o ~/.local/bin/opa \
#     https://openpolicyagent.org/downloads/latest/opa_linux_amd64_static && \
#     chmod +x ~/.local/bin/opa
# …or point at a wrapper / non-PATH binary:
# DOO_OPA_BIN=/path/to/opa
#
# The compose stack also runs OPA as a server on :8181 with the fixed Rego
# pre-loaded (see docker-compose.yml). An `OpaHttpClient` against that sidecar
# is the production-shaped path; `OpaEvalClient` (subprocess) is the default.
# DOO_OPA_URL=http://localhost:8181
#
# Per-engagement tester-authored deny rules (optional, ADR-0046):
# DOO_OPA_OVERLAY=./engagements/<id>/overlay.rego

# ----- Dispatch (slice 4 — `doo dispatch run` / `doo finding review`) -----
# The Interpreter reuses the DOO_PLANNER_* model config above. Set
# DOO_NO_INTERPRETER=1 for a primary-only smoke run (no LLM, no verdict).
# DOO_NO_INTERPRETER=
# DOO_DISPATCH_LEDGER_PATH=./.doo/dispatch_ledger.json
# DOO_FINDING_LEDGER_PATH=./.doo/finding_ledger.json

# ----- Engagement ledger (optional) -----
# Where `doo engagement start` records engagement ids. Defaults to
# ~/.doo/engagement_ledger.json; override to keep test runs out of your home dir.
# DOO_LEDGER_PATH=./.doo/engagement_ledger.json

# ----- AuthContext tokens (per ADR-0012: env-var references only in YAML) -----
# Put the real token values here and reference them as ${VAR_NAME} in the
# engagement YAML. Never inline a token in YAML. The fixture
# tests/fixtures/yaml/acme-test.yaml references ${DOO_TEST_TOKEN_A}:
# DOO_TEST_TOKEN_A=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJzdWIiOiJ1dWlkLWFhYSIsImV4cCI6NDEwMjQ0NDgwMH0.g32AFQCk2wGfExJCjL61A7bgUXAqwvfY1AF0-w5I-K0
